+# HTML Diff Artifact Design
+
+## Context
+
+`drydock` currently gives pull request reviewers two manifest diff surfaces:
+
+- a truncated markdown PR comment generated by `drydock diff apps -o markdown`;
+- a full raw unified diff text artifact written through `--raw-output-file`.
+
+The raw artifact preserves complete diff data, but it is hard to review in a
+browser. The PR action should add a lightweight static HTML artifact that makes
+large desired-state diffs easier to scan without changing the existing comment
+or text artifact behavior.
+
+## Goals
+
+- Generate a single self-contained `drydock-diff-<run>-<attempt>.html` file.
+- Upload the HTML file as a directly browser-openable GitHub Actions artifact.
+- Keep the existing raw text diff artifact for compatibility.
+- Build the report from structured drydock diff results, not by reparsing the
+  raw artifact as the primary data source.
+- Keep generation fast, offline, and native Go.
+- Avoid external assets, CDNs, npm build steps, browser frameworks, and
+  shellout renderers.
+
+## Non-Goals
+
+- Do not replace the markdown PR comment.
+- Do not remove or rename the existing raw diff artifact.
+- Do not add live Kubernetes, Argo CD, SCM API, or GitHub API behavior.
+- Do not implement a full source-file browser for unchanged rendered content.
+- Do not introduce a separate Go module or public API surface.
+
+## Architecture
+
+Add an internal renderer package, tentatively `internal/report/diffhtml`.
+The package exposes a small API that accepts `app.DiffResult` plus rendering
+options and returns or writes one HTML document.
+
+The renderer owns:
+
+- grouping resources by Application;
+- parsing unified diff hunks into display rows;
+- escaping all dynamic text and manifest content;
+- rendering summary, diagnostics, file tree, toolbar, and diff panes;
+- embedding CSS and minimal JavaScript inline.
+
+The CLI owns only wiring:
+
+- add `--html-output-file` to `diff apps` and `diff app`;
+- when the flag is set, write a full HTML report in addition to the selected
+  stdout format;
+- leave `-o` behavior unchanged.
+
+The PR action owns only action integration:
+
+- allocate an HTML output path in the action work directory;
+- pass `--html-output-file` when manifest diff is enabled;
+- expose `diff-html-path` and `diff-html-artifact-name` outputs;
+- upload the HTML artifact when `upload-artifacts=true` and `has-diff=true`.
+
+## HTML UX
+
+The page is a static review tool with a VS Code-like layout:
+
+- left pane: changed Applications and resources, grouped and searchable;
+- top summary: app/resource counts, added and removed line counts, diagnostics;
+- main pane: selected resource diff;
+- view toggle: side-by-side and unified modes;
+- change badges: added, removed, modified;
+- visual diff styling close to GitHub conventions;
+- lightweight YAML-oriented highlighting for keys, strings, comments, and
+  numbers where practical.
+
+The first implementation should prioritize navigation, readable diff rows,
+sticky headers, keyboard-safe focus behavior, and responsive layout over deep
+syntax highlighting. The report must work from a local `file://` open and from
+GitHub's artifact viewer.
+
+## Artifact Strategy
+
+The default PR-action behavior should upload the HTML file with
+`actions/upload-artifact@v7` using `archive: false`. This favors direct browser
+viewing over named zipped artifacts.
+
+Because unarchived single-file artifacts use the filename as the artifact name,
+the generated filename should be stable and descriptive:
+
+`drydock-diff-<GITHUB_RUN_ID or run>-<GITHUB_RUN_ATTEMPT or 1>.html`
+
+The existing raw text artifact keeps its current naming and upload behavior.
+The PR comment footer may link to the workflow run as it does today; once the
+HTML upload step has a stable artifact URL output, the comment can prefer the
+HTML artifact link while still mentioning the raw artifact when useful.
+
+## Data Flow
+
+1. `drydock diff apps` renders and diffs both desired-state sides as today.
+2. CLI receives `app.DiffResult`.
+3. CLI writes the existing selected stdout format.
+4. CLI writes the existing raw diff file when `--raw-output-file` is set.
+5. CLI writes the HTML file when `--html-output-file` is set.
+6. The PR action uploads the raw text artifact and the HTML artifact as separate
+   artifacts.
+
+HTML generation should use the same `app.DiffResult` used for markdown and raw
+output. That preserves existing diff semantics, secret redaction behavior,
+normalization, changed-only selection, and diagnostics.
+
+## Error Handling
+
+- Invalid HTML output paths should fail the CLI with `write HTML diff output`.
+- HTML generation errors should fail the command because the caller explicitly
+  requested an output file.
+- The PR action should treat an HTML generation failure the same way it treats a
+  manifest diff command failure.
+- If there is no manifest diff, the action should not upload an HTML artifact by
+  default.
+
+## Performance
+
+The renderer should be linear in the size of `app.DiffResult` and avoid
+expensive client-side parsing. It can embed the rendered report model directly
+as HTML or compact JSON, but should not require a large JavaScript runtime.
+
+The first implementation does not need an HTML size limit. If very large diffs
+create artifact-size or browser-performance issues, add an explicit
+`--html-max-bytes` or row virtualization design later.
+
+## Security
+
+- Escape all Application names, resource identifiers, diagnostic text, and diff
+  content before writing HTML.
+- Keep all assets inline and local.
+- Do not include repository credentials, tokens, credential-bearing URLs, or
+  Secret values beyond the existing diff redaction behavior.
+- Do not read ambient Git credentials, Helm registry config, or external
+  network resources for report generation.
+
+## Testing
+
+Focused tests should cover:
+
+- HTML escaping for names, diagnostics, and manifest content;
+- grouping by Application and resource;
+- added, removed, and modified resources;
+- hunk parsing and line number rendering;
+- side-by-side model generation;
+- empty diff behavior at the renderer level;
+- CLI writes `--html-output-file` without changing stdout;
+- PR action exposes and uploads HTML artifact paths when diffs exist;
+- docs mention the HTML artifact and raw artifact compatibility.
+
+## Settled Decision
+
+The initial action should use direct, unarchived HTML upload by default and keep
+the raw text artifact zipped/named as it is today. A future compatibility input
+can add zipped HTML behavior for environments that cannot use unarchived
+artifacts.
